WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:07.280
Welcome to the essential ideas of Ronald Coase.

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:12.000
One of Coase’s most significant contributions&nbsp;
to our understanding of how the economy worksis&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.240
his explanation of the importance of&nbsp;
transaction costs—the costs that people incur&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:21.920
when they exchange goods and services with others.
For example, it costs time and money to find a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:27.040
seller of the good or service a person wants to&nbsp;
buy. There are also bargaining and decision costs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:31.520
like how the price of a good or service is&nbsp;
determined and drawing up the contract associated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:36.640
with a sale. And then there are enforcement&nbsp;
costs, for example the courts, lawyer fees or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:41.120
other legal institutions involved in resolving&nbsp;
disputes after an exchange is completed.&nbsp;

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:45.200
Prior to Coase, economists&nbsp;
greatly underestimated, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:50.640
even ignored the importance of transaction costs.
Let’s explore this important idea with an example.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:56.480
Bob is a cyclist who wants to buy a new bike. And&nbsp;
Jane’s company builds and sells mountain bikes.&nbsp;

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:01.200
Traditionally, economists would assume&nbsp;
that Bob and Jane find each other,exchange&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:05.920
money for the bike, and everyone is better off.&nbsp;
But Coase’s insight is that it’s more complicated.&nbsp;

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:12.080
First, Bob has to decide what kind of bike he&nbsp;
wants, and perhaps what brand. That takes time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:17.520
and so imposes a cost on Bob. Having decided&nbsp;
what bike he wants to buy, he has to find a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:23.760
store that sells it and this, too, imposes a cost.&nbsp;
Having located and travelled to Jane’s bike shop,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:29.120
Bob and Jane have to agree on a price for the&nbsp;
bike Bob wants to buy. This negotiation, too,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:35.040
imposes a cost on both Bob and Jane. And Jane,&nbsp;
the seller, faces other transaction costs.&nbsp;

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:40.720
First, Jane had to advertise that she carries&nbsp;
this particular bike, and Jane needs to have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:43.821
lawyer review the contract she has with the&nbsp;
bike manufacturer so that she understands&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.821 --> 00:01:44.480
the obligations she has to Bob for the&nbsp;
proper functioning of the bike. And, she&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:48.560
pays a fee so that she can accept credit&nbsp;
cards, which Bob uses to buy the bike.&nbsp;

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:53.040
These transaction costs are present in&nbsp;
every exchange that occurs every day,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:57.760
and are sometimes so high, they impede or&nbsp;
even prevent exchanges from taking place.&nbsp;

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.960
Coase’s insight into the prevalence and&nbsp;
importance of transaction costs in the economy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:06.160
transformed the way economists&nbsp;
viewed how markets work.

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:08.160
For more information on Ronald Coase visit EssentialCoase.org, 

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:10.160
and to learn about more essential scholars, visit EssentialScholars.org

